In article <gradyCsF5tF.Muw@netcom.com>, Grady Ward <grady@netcom.com> wrote:
>Piet van Oostrum (piet@cs.ruu.nl) wrote:
>
>: How could the bad guys find out if you do it properly. Use a brand new
>: diskette, wear gloves :=), put the stuff encrypted with the recipients
>: public key on the diskette, and stuff it in a brand new envelope. Put the
>: thing in a mailbox in one of the Mega cities, preferably far from where you
>: live. Be sure to buy everything also far away and don't wet the stamp with
>: your saliva. It will cost them a lot of effort to detect who did it, even
>: more to prove it.
>
>Don't forget to use latex gloves designed for use in Class-100 or smaller
>clean room environments: they don't have talc or other microcrystalline
>lubricants like the medical versions have.

What's the problem with talc or other powders?  You still won't leave prints
on anything you mail, but whether there's talc or not, one has to destroy the
gloves, since the insides may bear prints, latent or otherwise.
